\f1\b  June 23, 1954.\
\

\f0\b0 \uc0\u55356 \u56812 \u55356 \u56807 
\f1\b On this day, Alan Turing
\f2\b0  (1912-1954) was born. He was an English mathematician, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_scientist"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 computer scientist}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logic"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 logician}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cryptanalysis"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 cryptanalyst}}, philosopher, and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_and_theoretical_biology"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 theoretical biologist}}. Turing was highly influential in the development of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Theoretical_computer_science"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 theoretical computer science}}, providing a formalisation of the concepts of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algorithm"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 algorithm}} and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computation"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 computation}} with the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Turing_machine"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Turing machine}}, which can be considered a model of a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/General-purpose_computer"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 general-purpose computer}}. Turing is widely considered to be the father of theoretical computer science and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Artificial_intelligence"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 artificial intelligence}}. Despite these accomplishments, he was never fully recognised in his home country during his lifetime due to his homosexuality and because much of his work was covered by the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Official_Secrets_Act"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Official Secrets Act}}.\cb1 \
\cb3 During the \cf4 WWII\cf2 , Turing worked at {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bletchley_Park"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Bletchley Park}}, Britain's {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cryptanalysis"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 codebreaking}} centre that produced {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ultra"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Ultra}} intelligence. For a time he led {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hut_8"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Hut 8}}, the section that was responsible for German naval cryptanalysis. Here, he devised a number of techniques for speeding the breaking of German {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cipher"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 ciphers}}, including improvements to the pre-war Polish {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bomba_(cryptography)"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 bombe}} method, an {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electromechanics"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 electromechanical}} machine that could find settings for the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Enigma_machine"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Enigma machine}}.\cb1 \
